description: Fish ecology survey traps

Jellyfish are common in River and some in its tidal pond. Up to 3” diameter in Spring. Have either brick-red or orange center cluster under clear dome (bell), some pinkish tentacles and sometimes red lower extremities . Can’t find this exact color in references. 
A similar jelly was ID as “Lion’s Mane” in Maryland (iNaturalist). This is the largest species in the world, up to 6 foot wide bell, solitary and usually in North Atlantic. Maybe smaller individuals in warmer seas (20” diam. bell) If this observ is Lion’s mane, it's a very immature one (small).
